# Alexander Cunningham, 5th Earl of Glencairn

**Alexander Cunningham, 5th Earl of Glencairn** (c. 1515 – 23 November 1574) was a [Scottish](/Scotland) nobleman, a staunch [Protestant](/Protestant) reformer, and a pivotal figure in the tumultuous era of the [Scottish Reformation](/Scottish_Reformation). Known for his unwavering commitment to the [Protestant](/Protestant) cause, Glencairn played a crucial role in shaping the religious and political landscape of 16th-century Scotland. His life was marked by defiance against Catholic authority, strategic alliances with key reformers like [John Knox](/John_Knox), and a legacy that solidified the [Cunningham](/Clan_Cunningham) family's influence in Scottish history.

## Early Life and Family

Alexander Cunningham was born around 1515, the son of [William Cunningham, 4th Earl of Glencairn](/William_Cunningham,_4th_Earl_of_Glencairn) and his first wife, Catherine Borthwick, daughter of [William Borthwick, 3rd Lord Borthwick](/William_Borthwick,_3rd_Lord_Borthwick). From an early age, Cunningham was immersed in the political and religious upheavals of his time. His father, a known [Protestant](/Protestant) sympathizer, ensured that Alexander was raised with a deep understanding of the reformist ideals that would later define his career.

By 1540, Cunningham, then styled as **Lord Kilmaurs**, had already begun to make his mark as a vocal advocate for religious reform. His early writings, including a satirical poem mocking the [Grey Friars](/Grey_Friars), demonstrated his sharp wit and unyielding criticism of the Catholic Church. This poem, later reprinted by [John Knox](/John_Knox) in his *History of the Reformation in Scotland*, showcased Cunningham’s ability to blend literary talent with political activism—a skill that would serve him well in the years to come.

Upon the death of his father in 1548, Cunningham succeeded as the **5th Earl of Glencairn**, inheriting not only the title but also the family’s seat at [Finlaystone House](/Finlaystone_House) in [Inverclyde](/Inverclyde). This estate, which had been the stronghold of the Earls of Glencairn and the chiefs of [Clan Cunningham](/Clan_Cunningham) since 1405, became a hub for reformist activity under his leadership.

## Role in the Scottish Reformation

### Early Advocacy and Alliance with Knox

Glencairn’s commitment to the [Protestant](/Protestant) cause became even more pronounced with the return of [John Knox](/John_Knox) to Scotland in 1555. Knox, a firebrand preacher and key architect of the [Scottish Reformation](/Scottish_Reformation), found a powerful ally in Glencairn. The earl not only attended Knox’s sermons but also provided him with protection and support, even as the Catholic authorities sought to suppress the reformist movement.

One of the most daring moments in Glencairn’s early reformist career occurred when Knox, at the behest of the [Earl Marischal](/William_Keith,_4th_Earl_Marischal), penned a letter to [Mary of Guise](/Mary_of_Guise), the Queen Regent of Scotland. The letter urged her to protect [Protestant](/Protestant) preachers and embrace the Reformation. Glencairn, with characteristic boldness, personally delivered the letter to the Queen Regent. Mary of Guise, after barely glancing at it, handed it to [James Beaton, Archbishop of Glasgow](/James_Beaton_(archbishop_of_Glasgow)), dismissing it as a "pasquil"—a term for a satirical or mocking piece. This act of defiance underscored Glencairn’s willingness to challenge authority in the name of his beliefs.

### The Covenant and the Lords of the Congregation

In 1556, Glencairn further solidified his role as a leader of the reformist movement by hosting Knox at [Finlaystone House](/Finlaystone_House). During this gathering, the sacrament of the [Lord's Supper](/Eucharist) was administered in the [Reformed](/Reformed_Church) tradition to Glencairn’s family and close associates—a radical act at a time when Catholic rituals still dominated Scottish religious life.

By December 1557, Glencairn had become one of the key figures behind the **Covenant**, a binding agreement among [Protestant](/Protestant) nobles to defend and promote their faith. This group, which came to be known as the **[Lords of the Congregation](/Lords_of_the_Congregation)**, represented a unified front against Catholic oppression and laid the groundwork for the eventual establishment of [Protestantism](/Protestant) as Scotland’s dominant religion.

### Military and Political Leadership

The year 1559 marked a turning point in Glencairn’s career as the [Scottish Reformation](/Scottish_Reformation) escalated into open conflict. In response to the Queen Regent’s crackdown on [Protestant](/Protestant) dissent, Glencairn and his relative, **Sir Hugh Campbell of Loudon**, the Sheriff of [Ayr](/Ayr), confronted Mary of Guise directly. When she dismissed their demands for [religious toleration](/Religious_toleration) with the cold remark that "promises ought not to be urged upon princes, unless they can conveniently fulfil them," Glencairn and Campbell retorted that if she would not honor her commitments, they would "renounce [their] allegiance." This bold declaration forced the Queen Regent to reconsider her actions, at least temporarily halting her persecution of Protestants.

Glencairn’s military prowess became evident in May 1559 when [Protestant](/Protestant) forces in [Perth](/Perth,_Scotland) found themselves under threat. Glencairn responded by raising an impressive force of **1,200 horse and 1,300 foot soldiers** from the western regions of Scotland. His leadership in this conflict demonstrated his ability to mobilize support and defend the reformist cause through both political and military means.

### The Reformation Parliament and Aftermath

The efforts of Glencairn and his allies culminated in the **[Scottish Reformation Parliament](/Scottish_Reformation_Parliament)** of 1560, which formally established [Protestantism](/Protestant) as the national religion of Scotland. In recognition of his contributions, Glencairn was appointed to the [Privy Council](/Privy_Council_of_Scotland) of [Mary, Queen of Scots](/Mary,_Queen_of_Scots), a position that allowed him to continue influencing Scottish politics.

In 1561, Glencairn was part of a diplomatic mission to [England](/England), where he, along with the [Earl of Morton](/James_Douglas,_4th_Earl_of_Morton) and [William Maitland of Lethington](/William_Maitland_of_Lethington), proposed a marriage alliance between [Queen Elizabeth I of England](/Queen_Elizabeth_I_of_England) and the [Earl of Arran](/Earl_of_Arran_(Scotland)), the heir to the Scottish throne. The proposal, intended to strengthen Anglo-Scottish relations, was ultimately rejected by Elizabeth, but it highlighted Glencairn’s role as a key diplomat in the post-Reformation era.

## Opposition to Mary, Queen of Scots

Glencairn’s relationship with [Mary, Queen of Scots](/Mary,_Queen_of_Scots) was fraught with tension. He was among the nobles who vehemently opposed her marriage to [Lord Darnley](/Henry_Stuart,_Lord_Darnley), viewing it as a threat to the stability of the [Protestant](/Protestant) regime. His opposition to the Queen’s policies reached a climax in June 1567, when he took command of the [Protestant](/Protestant) forces at the so-called "battle" of [Carberry Hill](/Carberry_Hill). Though the conflict was more of a standoff than a battle, Glencairn’s leadership was instrumental in pressuring Mary to surrender.

When the French ambassador arrived with a message from the Queen offering forgiveness if the rebels dispersed, Glencairn’s response was characteristically defiant: *"We came not to ask pardon for any offence we have done, but to grant pardon to those who have offended."* This statement encapsulated his unyielding stance against what he perceived as royal tyranny.

Following Mary’s imprisonment at [Lochleven Castle](/Lochleven_Castle) in June 1567, Glencairn took decisive action to eradicate symbols of Catholicism. He led a group of his followers to the **[Chapel Royal](/Chapel_Royal)** at [Holyroodhouse](/Holyroodhouse), where they systematically destroyed sacred images, demolished the [altar](/Altar), and defaced all religious ornaments. This act of iconoclasm was not merely vandalism but a deliberate statement of the triumph of [Protestantism](/Protestant) over the old Catholic order.

## Later Years and Legacy

Alexander Cunningham, 5th Earl of Glencairn, died on **23 November 1574**. He was buried in the family crypt at the **Glencairn Aisle** in [Kilmaurs](/Kilmaurs), East Ayrshire, a fitting resting place for a man who had dedicated his life to the cause of reform. He was succeeded by his eldest son, **[William Cunningham, 6th Earl of Glencairn](/William_Cunningham,_6th_Earl_of_Glencairn)**, who continued the family’s legacy in Scottish politics.

### Writings and Cultural Impact

Beyond his political and military achievements, Glencairn was also a man of letters. His satirical poem, *The Hermit of Allareit or Loretto*, written near [Musselburgh](/Musselburgh), was a scathing critique of the Catholic Church and its practices. Preserved in Knox’s *History of the Reformation* and later featured in **Sibbald’s Chronicle of Scottish Poetry**, the poem remains a testament to Glencairn’s sharp intellect and his ability to wield words as effectively as swords in the battle for reform.

### Heraldry

The heraldic arms of the Earls of Glencairn are described as follows:
- **Crest**: On a helmet with a coronet, a unicorn’s head.
- **Supporters**: Two conies (rabbits) sejant.
- **Motto**: *Couché. A shakefork.*

These symbols, rich in Scottish heraldic tradition, reflect the noble lineage and martial spirit of the Cunningham family.

## Historical Significance

Alexander Cunningham, 5th Earl of Glencairn, stands as one of the most influential figures of the [Scottish Reformation](/Scottish_Reformation). His unwavering commitment to [Protestantism](/Protestant), his strategic alliances with reformers like [John Knox](/John_Knox), and his leadership in both political and military arenas ensured the success of the reformist movement in Scotland. While his methods were often confrontational and his rhetoric uncompromising, his contributions were indispensable in shaping a nation that would eventually embrace [Protestantism](/Protestant) as its defining faith.

His legacy extends beyond his lifetime, influencing not only the religious landscape of Scotland but also the political dynamics of the [Peerage of Scotland](/Peerage_of_Scotland). The Cunningham family, under his leadership, became synonymous with reform, and their seat at [Finlaystone House](/Finlaystone_House) remained a symbol of [Protestant](/Protestant) resilience for generations.